\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 Subject: MORALE & PUBLIC OPINION MONTHLY REPORT - JUNE 1948 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484809 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 This report does not necessarily express the views or opinions of
\par this Branch but is a reflection of the morale and opinions of the general public.
\par 
\par GENERAL
\par 
\par 1. Currency reform has been almost the only topic of general conversation. Prior to it
s inception on 20th June the people attempted by all possible means to get rid of their surplus Reichmarks, and black market prices rose to fantastic heights, e.g. coffee was quoted at RM. 2,800 per lb.
\par 
\par 2. Little business was carried out either legally or on the black market as those in possession of saleable goods withheld them as far as possible in order to obtain new currency as payment.
\par 
\par 3. The reform generally has had a calming effect, especially on the lower salary grades who now feel that at
 long last their money will be worth something. The issue of 40 new marks to each person was praised as being fair to everyone, and the restricted amount has curtailed spending so that only the bare necessities are being purchased.
\par 
\par 4. Except at Banks and bakeries queues have almost disappeared and it would seem that the "buyers strike", which is being supported by the Trades Unions, is going to make itself felt on shopkeepers, especially those of them who have b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484809 een withholding necessary house}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 hold goods. Cinemas, theatres and restaurants are also suffering to a certain extent.
\par 
\par 5. It is regretted, however, that the same currency was not introduced in all four Zones, and the separate currency of the Eastern Zone is believed to be the final blow in completing the split between East and West.
\par 
\par 6. Reaction to the decisions of the London Conference is generally unpleasant. The Allies are being accused of exploitation of Germany's industries, especially in the proposed Ruhr control.
\par 
\par 7. The result of the "Volksbegehren" is not accepted as being of any great consequence, as many people have declared that without trouble they signed their names a number of times.
\par 
\par FOOD
\par 
\par 8. Increased supplies, the issue of the long awaited fat ration, and prompt delivery of current groups of fresh vegetables have relieved much of the tension in the food situation, one notable feature being that more trust is placed in recent promises o
f increased rations.
\par 
\par 9. Great resentment is expressed, however, against the Cuban sugar and dates issued this month. It is claimed that Cuban sugar contains only a very small percentage of cane sugar and a large amount of dust and dirt. It is interest
ing to note that the Communists are holding "the American capitalists behind the Marshal Plan" responsible for dumping on the German market "this useless filth which will ruin the health of German children and for which Germany will later have to pay clea
rly in dollars".
\par 
\par 10. The amount of dates issued in the last one or two periods is said to be as great as Germany in normal times consumed in a year, the reason given being that Iraq could offer Britain and the United States no other commodity in return
 for the arms they deliver her to protect their oil interests in Iraq against Soviet intrusion.
\par 
\par 11. For a few days prior to Sunday, 20th June, difficulty was experienced by many in obtaining certain food supplies, particularly bread, because wholesale
rs and retailers withheld stocks in anticipation of currency reform. Some businesses even closed down for holidays of one or two weeks and thereby aroused great bitterness, especially among housewives. Prom Monday, 21st June, however, criticism was consid
erably tempered by the general relief that food stuffs were not only obtainable, vegetables being in such good supply as to be non-rationed, but that prices were remarkably low.
\par 
\par FUEL
\par 
\par 12. There is a demand that the fuel question should now in the s
ummer months be revised so that the people may be guaranteed heating for next winter, even at the expense of industry's coal requirements. A worker who has to spend all his free time stealing coal to warm his hone is neither contented nor productive. If t
his worry is removed from his daily life production will increase considerably in both quantity and quality.
\par 
\par PUBLIC HEALTH 
\par 
\par 13. The usual fears have been expressed of the effect, especially on children, of the lack of wholesome food, good housing and foot-wear.
\par 
\par CLOTHING/HOUSEHOLD 
\par 
\par 14. Sharp comment has been made about the shortage of soap and other
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
washing materials, and the Occupation powers are accused of causing this shortage by: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7405905 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 (a) refusing whaling rights to Germany,
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459989 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 (b) dismantling soap producing factories, and
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459989 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 (c) curtailing certain productions the by-products of which would make soap.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
\par 15. The return to shops of household goods as a result of currency reform has brought mixed feelings to housewives who, while glad 
that many of their domestic difficulties can at last be overcome, are annoyed that so many household goods have been withheld by shop-keepers, and there is a general demand that action should even now be taken against the defaulters.
\par 
\par BLACK MARKET 
\par 
\par 16. The general opinions is that although the black market will not be "killed" by currency reform it will be severely hit; that only luxury commodities which are really scarce will be traded, and those at prices not much above normal. The return on Mond
ay, 21st June, to the
\par legitimate market of many commodities hitherto unobtainable there is quoted in support of this contention.
\par 
\par 17. Early fears that in the first few days black marketeers would "corner" a major amount of the new currency were soon found to be groundless, as the Kopfgeld of DM 40 was not sufficient to allow anyone to buy much more than the bare necessities of life.

\par 
\par MILITARY GOVERNMENT 
\par 
\par 18. Severe criticism is made of the enormous Occupation costs to be borne by the Germans, and Mil Gov, over-staffed and under-worked, is alleged to have about the same number of employees as the Hamburg State. The last st
raw is that even housemaids have to be paid for by the Germans. It is frequently said that "it will suit the English very well to live at our expense for years to come. They will never live in such luxury again, so naturally they have no desire to leave G
ermany. They may tell us that we are being sustained by the British taxpayer, but surely his contribution is not comparable with that of the Hamburg taxpayer who alone to date has to pay DM 400,000,000."
\par 
\par LOCAL AUTHORITIES 
\par 
\par 19. The people are now practically resigned to the fact that the resurrection of the Amtsschimmel and the over-staffed bureaucratic machine is now complete. They bow to the inevitable that the Beamte is once more a dictator.
\par 
\par 20. The personnel distributing new currency from Banks and other money exchange centres were praised for the patient and efficient manner with which they executed a difficult and trying task.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
21. The issue of ration cards, however, causes a general outcry against the inefficiency of the authorities. 
Firstly because the issue is started too late in the Lay, and secondly because of an apparent lack of planning. There are not sufficient distribution centres and the public to receive different cards must queue at separate counters. It is submitted that m
uch time would be saved and good feeling towards the authorities restored if each person could receive his full entitlement at one counter.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7405905 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 22. Senator DETTMANN and the Gesundheitsverwaltung are blamed for lack of action in the maintenance of ambulances
. It is alleged that these have not been renewed since before 1933 and that their condition is so deplorable that patients being conveyed in them suffer not only great discomfort but unnecessary pain.
\par 
\par TRAFFIC/TRANSPORT 
\par 
\par 23. A distinct drop in the number of persons using trams, underground, etc., was noticeable after the currency reform, due no doubt to the fact that little business was being Lone in the first few days.
\par 
\par 24. Residents in Lokstedter Steinweg and vicinity complain bitterly that o
n 13th June the street mentioned was completely blocked from 12 o'clock by persons desirous of attending a Football hatch H.S.V. v. St. Pauli in Viktoria Sportplatz Hoheluft, and expressed the opinion that with a little planning by the police and transpor
t authorities much annoyance could have been avoided.
\par 
\par POLICE
\par 
\par 25. During the exhibition of valuable Eastern collections in the Museum Fur Kunst und Gewerbe, two uniformed policemen were seen at all times patrolling, presumably to protect the colle
ctions. The public's reaction was first one of annoyance that they were not considered trustworthy, and secondly of surprise that the police authorities did not have the sense to place plain clothes officers on guard.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 26. The manner in which the poli
ce, with few exceptions, carried out their very important part in the currency reform has been very highly praised. In the majority of exchange centres they contrived to keep the crowds good-natured and friendly despite the facts that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459989 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 (a) the police themselves performed very long hours of duty;
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13459989 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid7405905 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 (b) the public had to stand in queues for many hours. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
\par ECONOMY
\par 
\par 27. The Ordinance No.54 dealing with the direction of labour has caused a fair amount of unrest, e.g. a man in Altona already in steady employment with a private firm received an order to report for work with the building authorities. One paragraph of 
the Order stated that failure to comply would render him liable to punishment by a CCG court. Such action is likened to certain labour recruitment measures alleged to be carried out in the Soviet Zone. Direction, especially to hard physical labour, of bla
c
k marketeers and other dodgers, would be welcome, but it is felt that under this Ordinance the local Labour Office is not only showing its own weakness and inefficiency but is hiding behind the skirts of the Occupation Powers in puerile attempts to carry 
out its own urgent responsibilities.
\par 
\par 28. Difficulty is being experienced in obtaining apprentices for some trades which make heavy demands on clothing, footwear, and cleaning materials, and which require a certain physical standard. In view of the pres
ent shortages many parents prefer their children to be "black-coated" workers. The only solution suggested is that special attractions in the form of increased wages and leave be offered for "dirty" trades.
\par 
\par 29. The 25% reduction in Marshal Aid has rai
sed some doubts as to the sincerity of the U.S. desire to assist in Europe's economic reconstruction. Leftish elements proclaim the reduction to have been necessitated by the American rearmament programme, and frequently quote the old Nazi cry "Guns or Bu
t
ter". They also warned the public against clutching at a straw in their present difficulties, that they will have no choice but to accept only inferior goods, and that they will have to pay dearly in future years for blind faith in American promises. It i
s generally expected, however, that the Marshal Plan will give genuine material assistance to Germany and do much to counteract Soviet propaganda.
\par 
\par 30. Despite current shortages, supplies of manufactured goods, particularly clothing, are not welcome, th
e overwhelming opinion being that Germany lacks neither plant nor labour and can gain infinitely more from the import of raw materials equivalent in dollar value to the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1408191 manufactured goods which J.E.I.A.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 now forces her to accept.
\par 
\par 31. German Merchant S
eamen "who have committed no war crimes and who today have nothing to lose and everything to gain" have been strongly supported by public opinion in their demands for an opportunity to resume their calling. Germany would thereby be saved the enormous frei
ght charges paid to foreign Companies at present handling her imports and exports, and the reconstruction, maintenance, and manning of the Merchant Fleet would provide employment for thousands of idle shipbuilders and seamen.
\par 
\par 32. There is a distinct no
te of confidence in business circles that many of the fears expressed before the inception of currency reform are now proved groundless and that the new Mark will soon find a good value in the world market and be of infinite assistance in the restoration 
o
f German economy. It is felt, however, that the latter is to no small extent hindered by the fact that German initiative and industry are not alone responsible but have to labour under the many difficulties and hindrances imposed through the Joint Export 
& Import Agency by large British and American business interests.
\par 
\par DENAZIFICATION 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1408191 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1408191 
33. The complete stoppage of work by the German Denazification Authorities in Hamburg and the resignation from Denazification bodies by S.P.D. members in North Rhine Westphalia are very popular because the general opinion is and always has been that}{
